I now have the complete picture from the knowledge graph. Let me deliver the full diagnosis with the documented fix pattern.

---

## Diagnosis

The cap-height of IBM Plex Serif glyphs is being cropped at the top edge of the `<input>` element. Critically, you already identified the tell: **increasing `padding-top` made the input taller but did not move the glyph**. That precise symptom is the fingerprint of the documented anti-pattern — it's not a padding problem at all.

---

## Root Cause — AP-064 / EAP-077

> **AP-064: Native `<input>` Text Rendering for Display-Scale Serif Fonts**
> **EAP-077: Assuming CSS Can Fix `<input>` Native Text Clipping for Oversized Serif Fonts**

The root cause is a three-layer problem that compounds at display scale:

### Layer 1 — The browser's internal `<input>` line-box model

A native `<input>` renders its text inside a **browser-controlled inner UA shadow subtree**. The browser sizes this inner text container using its own internal algorithm based on the element's computed `font-size` and `line-height`. At body-copy sizes (14–18 px) this is invisible; the glyph ascender fits inside the UA's internal allocation with room to spare.

At display scale (`heading-case-study-intro` is `clamp(36px, …, 60px)` / IBM Plex Serif Medium 500), the glyph's **ascender extends above the cap-height by a significant amount** — IBM Plex Serif has an unusually tall internal leading (`ascender + descender > UPM`). The browser's internal input text box simply does not allocate enough vertical space for that ascender, and it is **clipped by the UA's own internal overflow boundary**, not by any CSS property you own.

### Layer 2 — Why `padding-top` is a no-op for the clip

`padding-top` on an `<input>` affects the space between the element's border-box and its **internal text content area**. It does **not** expand the internal UA line box that the browser allocates for the text rendering itself. You're pushing air into a room whose ceiling is managed by the browser, not by CSS. The glyph's ascender still hits that internal ceiling — it just hits it with more space below it now, which makes the input taller without fixing the crop. This is the exact symptom you observed.

### Layer 3 — `line-height` on `<input>` is partially honoured, but not for glyph overflow

Setting `line-height` on a native `<input>` changes the logical height of the line box the browser allocates. **However**, at display scale with a high-ascender serif, even a generous `line-height: 1.4` can still clip because the browser clips at the element's padding-box, not at the line-height allocation. The ascender of IBM Plex Serif at 60 px can extend ~15 px above the cap-height line — that spike disappears behind the padding-box edge regardless.

The **canonical fix** from ENG-139/ENG-141 (and the pattern used on the login page in FB-129) is: **replace the `<input>` with a `contenteditable` `<div>`**. A `div` respects its own `overflow: visible` by default; glyph ascenders are never clipped by a UA shadow boundary because there is no UA shadow boundary.

---

## The Fix

### 1. Locate the component

The display-scale title field in the case-study editor is almost certainly the `introBlurbHeadline` editable field. Based on the inline-edit architecture (§14 of `engineering.md`), it will be rendered by the `EditableText` primitive or a bespoke field component. Find it:

```
src/app/(admin)/
src/components/inline-edit/
src/components/case-study/
```

Grep for the element:
```bash
grep -r "display-scale\|titleInput\|introBlurbHeadline\|heading-case-study-intro" \
  src/ --include="*.tsx" --include="*.scss" -l
```

### 2. Replace `<input>` with `contenteditable`

**Before (broken):**
```tsx
// SomeTitleInput.tsx
<input
  className={styles.displayTitle}
  value={value}
  onChange={e => onChange(e.target.value)}
/>
```

```scss
// SomeTitleInput.module.scss
.displayTitle {
  @include heading-case-study-intro;   // IBM Plex Serif, clamp 36–60px, weight 500
  padding-top: 12px;                   // ← this does nothing for the glyph clip
  padding-bottom: 8px;
  width: 100%;
  border: none;
  background: transparent;
}
```

**After (fixed):**
```tsx
// SomeTitleInput.tsx  — drop-in replacement, same external API
import { useRef, useEffect } from 'react'
import styles from './SomeTitleInput.module.scss'

interface Props {
  value: string
  onChange: (next: string) => void
  placeholder?: string
}

export function DisplayTitleInput({ value, onChange, placeholder }: Props) {
  const ref = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null)

  // Keep DOM in sync when value changes externally (CMS load, undo, etc.)
  useEffect(() => {
    const el = ref.current
    if (!el || el.textContent === value) return
    el.textContent = value
  }, [value])

  return (
    <div
      ref={ref}
      role="textbox"
      aria-label="Case study title"
      aria-multiline="false"
      contentEditable
      suppressContentEditableWarning
      className={styles.displayTitle}
      data-placeholder={placeholder}
      onInput={e => onChange((e.currentTarget as HTMLDivElement).textContent ?? '')}
      onKeyDown={e => {
        // Prevent Enter from inserting a <br> / new block
        if (e.key === 'Enter') {
          e.preventDefault()
        }
      }}
      // Paste as plain text — strip any rich formatting
      onPaste={e => {
        e.preventDefault()
        const text = e.clipboardData.getData('text/plain')
        document.execCommand('insertText', false, text)
      }}
    />
  )
}
```

```scss
// SomeTitleInput.module.scss
.displayTitle {
  @include heading-case-study-intro;  // IBM Plex Serif, clamp 36–60px, weight 500

  // ── Glyph-safe vertical breathing room ──────────────────────────────────
  // A div respects overflow:visible by default, so ascenders never clip.
  // Add explicit vertical padding that accounts for the Plex Serif ascender
  // spike (~0.25em above cap-height at this scale).
  padding-block: 0.3em;             // ← in em so it scales with the fluid font-size

  // ── Layout ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  display: block;
  width: 100%;
  min-height: 1.4em;                // prevents collapse when empty
  outline: none;
  border: none;
  background: transparent;
  cursor: text;
  white-space: nowrap;              // single-line behaviour mirrors <input>
  overflow: hidden;                 // clip long text horizontally...
  text-overflow: ellipsis;          // ...with ellipsis (reading mode only)

  // ── Placeholder ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  &:empty::before {
    content: attr(data-placeholder);
    color: var(--color-foreground-subtle);  // use your design token
    pointer-events: none;
  }

  // ── Focus state ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  // When editing, remove overflow clip so the full line is visible while typing
  &:focus {
    overflow: visible;
    text-overflow: clip;
    white-space: pre;
  }
}
```

> **⚠️ EAP-080 trap**: the `overflow: hidden` on the resting state is safe here because it's applied to a `div`, not an `<input>`. A `div`'s overflow clips at the element's own padding-box edges, which you control. The glyphs already have room from `padding-block: 0.3em`. The `:focus` state removes the clip entirely so ascenders are always visible while typing. Never put `overflow: hidden` directly on a display-scale text container without first ensuring glyph-safe padding (EAP-080).

---

### 3. If `overflow: hidden` is required in resting state (e.g., for the read-only overlay)

Use the **two-element wrapper pattern** (documented in ENG-141). This comes up if the parent layout clips at its own boundary:

```tsx
<div className={styles.titleWrapper}>         {/* owns overflow:hidden + sizing */}
  <div className={styles.displayTitle} …/>    {/* contenteditable, overflow:visible */}
</div>
```

```scss
.titleWrapper {
  overflow: hidden;                  // layout clip lives HERE, on the non-text element
  padding-block: 0.3em;             // the glyph padding is on the wrapper, not the text el
}

.displayTitle {
  @include heading-case-study-intro;
  overflow: visible;                 // never hidden on the glyph-bearing element
  outline: none;
  white-space: nowrap;
  background: transparent;
  border: none;
  cursor: text;
}
```

---

### 4. Verify

After the swap, confirm in DevTools:
1. The element in the DOM is a `<div>`, not an `<input>`.
2. `overflow: visible` is the computed value on the text element in `:focus`.
3. Resize the browser to the fluid font-size extremes (mobile 36 px, desktop 60 px) — check cap-heights at both ends.
4. Paste rich text → should arrive as plain text.
5. Press Enter → should be swallowed (no `<br>` inserted).

---

## Why This Is Structurally Different for Display-Scale Fonts

Here is the precise mechanical explanation:

| Factor | Body-copy `<input>` (14–18 px) | Display-scale `<input>` (36–60 px, serif) |
|--------|--------------------------------|------------------------------------------|
| **UA inner text box height** | Browser allocates ≈ `font-size × 1.2` — comfortably contains the relatively short ascender of Geist Sans | Same `×1.2` formula, but IBM Plex Serif's ascender ratio is ~0.73 UPM above baseline. At 60 px that's ~44 px of space above the baseline — the UA allocation often falls short |
| **Ascender overshoot** | < 2 px at 16 px — invisible | 10–18 px at 60 px — obviously visible crop |
| **`padding-top` effect** | Moves text downward relative to element border, which incidentally fixes minor clips | Moves text downward, but the UA's own inner box ceiling doesn't move — the clip point is internal to the UA, not at the CSS padding edge |
| **`line-height` effect** | Expands the logical line box, fully fixes minor UA clips | Partially expands allocation, but IBM Plex Serif's metrics can still overflow because the font's internal ascender vector extends above what `line-height` controls |
| **Why `<div contenteditable>` fixes it** | Not needed at body scale | A `div` has no UA shadow-DOM text container. The browser renders glyphs into the element's own box, which respects `overflow: visible` by default. The ascender floats above the content area edge with zero clipping |
| **`overflow: hidden` risk** | Safe at body scale (ascenders don't reach the boundary) | Must never be applied to the glyph-bearing element without first adding `padding-block ≥ 0.3em` (EAP-080) |

**The mental model:** A native `<input>` is two boxes — the CSS box you control and a UA-managed inner text box you cannot control. At body scale the UA box is large enough that you never see the boundary. At display scale with a high-ascender serif, the UA box becomes the **ceiling**, and CSS has no lever that raises it. The fix is to remove the UA box entirely by using a host element (`div`) that has no UA text container.

---

## Principle

> **AP-064 / EAP-077 — Display-scale serif fonts must never be rendered inside a native `<input>` or `<textarea>`.** Replace with `contenteditable div`. CSS padding and `line-height` adjustments on `<input>` cannot fix UA-managed glyph clipping at display scale — they treat a symptom that lives inside the browser shadow boundary, not in the CSS box model. The fix is structural, not stylistic.
